segments.text: Court trip to Fort Worth.
Fort Worth.
Describe that.
Oh, that was hectic.
I was just a young kid.
No money or anything like that, but I had tickets to the football game.
Well, we get there in this room, and we had all these Aggies, all freshmen.
We were all in there, and, you know, there wasn't much drinking.
Hardly any drinking at all.
There was some that liked it at that age, and I never drank at all at A&M except when we had the fish party.
And that's the last time I drank at A&M, believe me.
My whole four years I never drank any alcohol at all, or smoked cigarettes.
But at TCU, in the same hotel with girls from Tissy, from Denton.
and TSCW and they were there and so it was really a nice party and nothing permissive was about it at all.
It was just wholesome fun and they knew we didn't have any money so they didn't care about making demands on us.
We all went to the game together and we all came back and we had good bull session with the girls and everything.
And then about 3 o'clock in the morning, 2 o'clock in the morning, everybody decided they better go to sleep.
Everybody left.
And you marched down the street in the review.
Yes, sir.
Any negative?
Did anything ever happen badly during a formal review?
I can't recall anything.
The crowd cheered us every time we'd come by.
They cheered and cheered and cheered and it just made you feel proud to be an Aggie.
That fall, there must have been some special football moments that you remember because we had a pretty good team that fall.
We had a good team, great national champions.
Yes.
What were some favorite moments you remember?
Well, every game we had at College Station was a great moment because we had this guy named Jordan John Kimbrough.
We'd holler for Joran John, Joran John.
So even the Texas game, we were never worried about it.
But we used to farm, we used to have, we farmed the tea, block tea, which they don't do now.
And the Yale leaders would get on top of the press box and we'd be on the cow field, farmed in tea.
And I think that was just great.
Now, during that year, that fall, describe a typical home Saturday.
You got up and... Oh, Saturday morning, the day of the game.
Everybody's excited.
Go to breakfast, wait tables, and then go back.
And noon was a great occasion because here comes, well, yeah, my fish year.
I was just a freshman with a white jacket on, and the girls were all there.
But my senior year, when I was waiting tables for a typical football game, had the boots on, and the girls admired the boots, and you come up with those.
starchy white jackets, you know, you really made a nice presentation.
And the girls would go, oh, oh, oh, you know.
But a typical day, everybody was in a hurry to get to the game, and we all sat together, just like they do today.
And then we watched the ball game, and of course,
Was there a Friday night Yale practice?
Midnight, yes, we had midnight Yale practice.
And it was held at the Y?
At the Y, on the steps of the YMCA, sure were, right there by the bugle stand.
Describe your memory of some of these famous football, Aggie football players.
What was John Kimbrough like as a person?
John Kimbrough as a person, and I really got to know him because I was a freshman football player.
but as a person was genuinely one of the finest persons I've met from Haskell, Texas.
Always accommodating, always smiling, and always doing the right thing and never bad mouthing anybody.
great All-American guard A&M had, tough as they make them boy.
He was just opposite of John.
But he was pleasant too.
He was a nice guy.
He never abused anybody.
And Jim Thomason was sort of a quiet person, but he was the leading blocker for Kimbrough.
Herb Smith was the end.
And just Cotton Price was a quarterback.
And did all those football players go to class?
They all went to class.
They lived in dorms.
If they didn't live with their unit, and I lived with my unit, A battery, then I got transferred to H battery.
But we had dorm 12, was the athletic dorm.
And if the athletes didn't want to live with the unit, they lived over there.
Now they were kind of a rowdy bunch over there.
Yeah, he couldn't study in there.
But they didn't get any give-away grades.
No.
They had to go to class like everybody else.
Oh, no.
In fact, I think the profs made it tougher on us.
Who were some of the other famous students when you were here?
Kimbrough and, you mentioned Kimbrough and Robinette.
Who were some of the other celebrities?
Celebrities?
Today, you mean?
Uh-huh.
Bob Bright.
Went from Dallas.
He happened, his name was Bright and my name was Cocono so when we stood in line alphabetically he was always in front of me and I said, what's your name?
He said Bright.
Where you from, Dallas?
Where you from, Beaumont?
So we became dear friends.
I didn't know who he was.
He didn't know who I was.
Did he have that nickname then?
Oh, yeah.
How did he get that, do you know?
I have no idea how Bum got that name.
But what a fine person.
Who were some other famous Aggies that you knew as students?
At that time, other than athletes, I'm trying to think.
Well, who were your best buddies, your best friends, when you were a student?
Well, my basketball comrade were friends, Raymond Clutch, Pete Watkins, who held the high jump record at Drake for 20-some odd years, and who else?
Daddy Green, the swimming All-American.
You want to hear that story?
Yes, please.
I'm sitting on the basketball bench one afternoon my junior year when I was resting.
We were practicing and Coach Art Adamson
You know, he wasn't a very outgoing person, but he was a nice guy, really nice.
Never said much to anybody, but he always put out winners.
World champion water polo team and swimmers and Danny Green, All-American.
And he comes sitting down beside me.
I looked at him and said to myself, that's unusual.
He never sits by anybody, you know.
So next thing I know, he's asking me, he says, Mike, I understand you're quite a swimmer.
And, you know, I'm thinking, what's he going, what's he leading up to?
I said, no, I'm not, coach.
I'm a terrible swimmer.
I hadn't swam since I've been here.
He said, well, I didn't come to ask you to be on the swimming team.
I come to ask you to be my diver.
I said, what?
Diver?
How did you know I dive?
He said, I looked it up in the
Beaumont, Texas YMCA office, they told me you won the state championship diving and everything.
He said, he said, my diver quit and I need a diver.
Won't you help me?
Boy, and I was coming from Coach Adamson, that's something.
He said, sure coach.
So I was the diver for the A&M swimming team and then I think the record will reflect that out of eight
colleges at the conference meet, came out fifth.
Pretty good.
Now, did he give you any scholarship?
No, sir.
It was all for free?
All free, volunteer.
What year was that that you joined swimming?
It was 41-42 year.
So, your third year.
My third year.
When you first got here, the YMCA was the social center?
It was a gathering point.
Yeah.
Describe what all y'all did at the YMCA.
Well they had, I didn't go there very often because I was too busy doing other things, but they had a pool table and people playing pool and ping pong.
And it was there where the Y, I think it's still there, in that same building.
Only they didn't have very many, they didn't have much room, but I think they've accumulated more room today.
But it was, I'm trying to remember the director of the Y. Cashin.
Cashin.
Mr. Cashin.
He sure was.
And it was just,
a small area to go to and get away from everything and it was nice.
Mr. Cashin, that's right.
Did you ever see his two little boys, Red and Jim?
Let me tell you about Red.
When I was a varsity basketball player, Red was about 12 years old.
And he would, somehow we got to be dear friends.
And he would wait for me the day of the game at the front.
I said, you wait for me at the gate when I get there and I'll take you into the game.
He said, yes sir.
And so he'd wait, when I'd come up he'd be there waiting.
I said, come on in Red, come on in.
Let him in, he's with me.
And so we'd go to the locker room and he'd get my sweat clothes and he'd get my tape and make sure my ankles were taped right.
What an experience and what a guy he is today.
But every game, Red was waiting for me at the gate.
Share some memories of that first basketball season here for you.
For me?
I was a sophomore.
Oh, so freshmen, you all didn't play games?
We didn't play a scheduled game.
I was a sophomore.
And start practicing, practice, practice.
For some reason or another, Coach McQuillan let me be the point guard.
And the point guard was a senior named Sammy Dwyer.
He was a senior.
I don't know if I was hurting his feelings or not.
I was kind of concerned about that.
But anyway, I played quite a bit my sophomore year.
And in my junior year, I completely took over the point guard.
And in my senior year, Marty Corot had got called up in the service.
And Manning Smith was our coach.
And Manning came to me.
I was captain of the team.
He said, Mike, I never played basketball.
I never coached basketball.
I don't think about it.
I need help.
I said, it's OK, coach.
Here's our plays.
And I diagrammed them for him.
And we went over the roster and became acquainted.
But it was a nice year of basketball for me.
What were some of the favorite games that you have in your heart, in your memory?
Kentucky and A&M.
We were on a trip during the Christmas holiday.
This was back in 42.
We were on the way to the Madison Square Garden.
We were going to play Oregon State in Madison Square Garden.
And we started off playing LSU.
Anyway we finally wind up playing Bradley Tech and we got to Kentucky and we played eight in Kentucky.
Well at the half they were beating us pretty bad.
And so the team rallied, and I was pushing, pushing, pushing, pushing.
And it scared Adolph Rupp, the coach.
Scared him, man.
Going to get beat by that old college down in Texas.
And so anyway, they beat us not

bad but they beat us and after the game he went to shake manning smith's hand and he said no coach i want to shake that little bitty guy's hand he scared me i thought he was going to tear us up and so coach rupp came over to shut my hand i have not watched it since
Oh yeah, that's a memorable memory for me.
And playing in Madison Square Garden, who'd you all play?
Oh, they canceled it.
So we played Oregon State and Springfield, Illinois.
Now did you make that trip on the train or on bus?
On the train.
On the train.
We stayed on the Pullman.
And about how many teams?
It was ten of us.
Ten?
Yes, sir.
And we all stayed on.
We played Kentucky, LSU, Bradley Tech, Purdue.
Piggy Lamberth was the co-chair.
And then we swung around and played Oregon State and Springfield, Illinois.
Then we swung around and played George Washington University.
And then we'd come on home.
I was going to tell you a story about
Oh, we were playing SMU one day, one night, my senior year.
And we were having a tough time with them.
You know, we didn't have an outstanding club, but we had a good fighting bunch.
And at the half, they were ahead of us about six points.
And we rallied and played and played hard.
And in fact, I made a couple of buckets.
If you made more than six points, you were quite a scorer, you know.
But I wasn't a scorer, I was a ball handler.
And I played so hard, and we won the game, that I just sat down in the middle of the floor.
I was just so tired.
And here comes a coed out of the grandstand.
and gives me a big hug and a kiss.
Next morning, Dallas Times Herald, Darling of the Courts.
And they had a picture of it.
And the caption was, Darling of the Courts beat SMU.
And that, you know, it was Bob Smith out of Houston's niece.
Yeah.
Did you get teased by your teammates?
Oh yeah, they always called me Darling.
Hey Darling, come on Darling.
But it was all in fun.
But we had a nice group.
Marty Corot was called up and went to Corpus Christi on active duty and we played his team there at the Naval Station.
And you were doing basketball strictly for fun, right?
Did you ever get a full scholarship?
Never did.
I don't know why.
So you continued to wait tables.
Wait tables and do odd jobs around.
And I don't know why I didn't make a demand since I was captain of the team to get a full scholarship.
If y'all had a full muscle or a health problem, who took care of that while you were an athlete?
We had a trainer named Little Demmon.
I called him Bubba Little.
He used to coach at Beaumont High School when I was there.
And he was the trainer.
If we had a big problem, we had to go to the hospital here.
Dr. Marsh was the doctor.
Very fine person.
Describe your memory of Dr. Marsh.
Oh, that rascal.
He was, you know, he was much older than we were.
But he got along great with the students.
I got along good with him.
And I never had any

problems with him at all i mean any any medical problems let me say did y'all call it the quack shack no we didn't call it later that would be the nickname yeah i know that that's what they call the clinic here or something who was the when you got here who was the president a m president walton teal walton describe him
Well he was, we didn't get, we weren't very much in touch with him.
And I don't want to, he lived in the President's house which was behind dorm ten in the corps area.
And he was pretty rough on the corps and stuff like that.
And one of my roommates drowned him out through the window of his home.
And of course, they caught him, suspended him, and told him they can never come back to A&M.
But I think a year later, they let him be in there.
Did you know the Gilchrists?
Gib Gilchrist was president, I think, after Mr. Walton.
And one year, I think, my senior year.
All right.
And then Henry was growing up on the campus.
They got here, I think, in 37 or 38.
and Henry was about ten, he told me, when he got here.
Oh, really?
So he would have been probably junior high, senior high when you got here.
Let's see.
Henry.
Henry Gilchrist.
Gilchrist, I see.
The son.
He's a lawyer in Dallas now.
Yeah.
Guyon Hall.
Guyon Hall was a musical hall, theater hall.
Yeah.
Didn't have money.
to go often, but when I did it was a treat.
Oh yeah, Guy and Hall.
Now I've heard that Aggies made noise during the movie sometimes, would cheer and laugh.
If that comes later?
That comes later.
During those first, particularly that first year or two, how did you communicate with your parents?
Did you all write letters?
Did you call on the phone?
Called letters.
Never called on the phone.
I don't recall calling on the phone.
How often would you write?
Write maybe at least once a week.
And one weekend I came home, and I'd been home several times, and my mother says, come, Andrew doesn't come home.
That's my brother.
He was a freshman behind me.
I said, well, Mama, he's studying.
And I said, she said, well, I wanted him to come home.
I hadn't seen him.
I said, OK, Mama, we'll get him here.
About the second month, we were in school.
And I had been home a couple of times.
The reason Andrew didn't get home, he was on a bull ring.
Every weekend, he was here at A&M.
So what happened?
I said, Andrew, let's do this.
I'm going to walk the bull ring for you.
weekend and you go home and see mama."
So he said, okay.
So I get down to the bullring, which is held behind the petroleum building, geology building.
They call it Coconose AP.
I had my campaign hat on and I looked down, here sir.
And they said, okay, and we start marching.
The first hour went well.
Then the second hour, here comes
Captain Elwood, our professor of military science, Red Elwood.
And he was watching us all, and he sent a sergeant over at the break, 10-minute break, and he said, go get Kokonos.
I want to talk to him.
So I get up in front of him, and I salute him and everything.
And he says, what in the H-E-L-L-U doing on this bullring?
He says, you don't have a demerit at all.
I know.
I've checked your record.
I said, sir, my brother Andrew is walking in the pool and I'm walking in his place.
Yeah, I know.
So Mama hadn't seen him since he came in there in September and this was about November.
And I said, Andrew, you go home and see Mama and I'll walk the bullring for you.
He looked at me and he looked at me.
Get back in line.
That's all he said.
But he turned out to be one of my finest friends and my mentor here at A&M.
He came to every basketball game.
He hollered for me at every play and every time I got the ball.
And he taught me how to fire
field artillery weapons as a forward observer that I used in combat.
And I really have a very dear spot in my heart for
Well, Colonel Elwood, when he left here.
Because he and I were very good friends.
All right.
And you mentioned combat.
Let's go back.
You got here as a freshman almost exactly when the war began in Europe in the fall of 1939.
That's right.
Did you and your buddies, did you all start talking much about the war in Europe?
Never said anything about it.
We didn't even consider it.
When I came to A&M, I couldn't do right face from left face.
I didn't know what military was really.
But I learned pretty quick.
What hurt us more, and I say us because it involves the basketball team,
In December of 41, we were practicing basketball and December 7, Coach Corot, I think it was a Sunday, called us all in the middle of the floor of D-Ware Gym.
He said, sit down fellas, I got something to tell you.
He said, Pearl Harbor was attacked by the Japanese and we're at war.
And would you believe it?
It wasn't a dry eye in the bunch.
They all were so mad and so hit hard by that that Coach Corot canceled the basketball practice and said come back Monday and we'll practice and sent us home.
What did you and, when you and your buddies as you went into the shower and went back to your room, what were you all saying to each other?
Not much.
We were really solemn.
We didn't know what to say.
Didn't know what to do, really.
But we knew if we stayed at A&M, we'd be trained to go wherever they wanted us to go.
And so we didn't say much.
There wasn't any big discussion.
They were all mad at the Japs for what they did.
As a history teacher, I can tell you that one of the now amusing things is to have a student ask, well, what about the opponents of the war?
We always tell them, there were none.
There were none.
And did some of your acquaintances leave quickly?
Yeah some of them did leave.
They joined up, they went to Canada and joined the Air Force.
But most of them stayed here.
And then we thought we were going to get our commission and be commissioned as second lieutenant, like they had done the other classes.
But they didn't do that to our class.
We went to school 12 months out of the year, and we didn't go to that summer training, six-week training.
That's where you get your commission and everything.
Now, had you gone to, after your freshman year, let's back up.
After your freshman year, what did you do that summer?
Did you go to summer camp after your freshman year?
No, sir.
You went back to Beaumont?
Went back to Beaumont and went to work.
What did you do?
Worked out the mobile oil refinery.
Good job.
Yeah, it was a water bar.
But they wouldn't keep it.
They wouldn't keep us.
And then next summer I worked for a pure oil company working on the labor gang out at Port Natchez.
And academically, how were you doing here?
Average.
I wasn't the brightest thing that came to A&M, but I was average.
And you changed your major from pre-med?
From engineering to pre-med.
Oh, you changed from engineering to pre-med.
Yes, sir.
And did you really think you were going to go to medical school?
I really thought I would go to medical school.
I sure did.
Who did you turn to for academic advice?
what to take and what instructors.
Who did you... You see, my advisor at the time
I didn't seek his advice.
He didn't ask me either.
He didn't call me in.
I was trying to think of the prof's name in the biology department, a little short fellow.
Anyway I visited with him and he told me what courses to take like genetics and histology and comparative anatomy.
But it was pretty well spelled out.
Take all the chemistry there was.
I took every chemistry course they had.
And I could have got a degree in chemistry if I'd have taken calculus or thermodynamics or something like that, but I wasn't very good at math, and so I avoided it.
But I really didn't seek anybody.
I just followed the course at A&M and sat down for pre-med.
Now, did you turn to an older brother for advice sometimes?
Yeah, my older brother was the one that talked me into taking engineering, which I didn't want to do it, so I didn't talk to him anymore.
You mentioned baptism a while ago, baptism in the Greek Orthodox Church.
Yes, sir.
Is that the church you, did you attend Greek Orthodox back in Beaumont?
Back in Beaumont, yes.
All right, now when you came up here, what did you do on Sundays?
I went to the Episcopalian Church.
down on behind Duncan Hall.
Right over here.
Right over here, yes, sir.
And I was a lay reader.
Did the typical Aggie go to church in those days?
Yes, they did.
Two or three of us used to march across the field behind Duncan Hall and go to church together.
In fact, Reverend Houser was the priest, the pastor, and he's a handball player.
So I'm a handball player.
So we got acquainted real quick.
good and bonded and so I went for four years.
Where did you play handball?
Behind DeWare Gym.
Outdoors?
No sir.
Oh in a little?
In a little shack behind it and the roof was
The ceiling was made of chicken wire, so you couldn't get a ceiling shot.
You familiar with handball?
I play handball today.
Hey, that's why you're in good shape.
Yes, sir.
I hope so.
Describe the religious activities on the campus.
Was there a religious emphasis week then in the spring?
They had them, but they weren't publicized very much.
We didn't have the chapel like they have here now.
My other roommate, Bobby Woodham, was a Baptist, and he went to the Baptist church, and I went with him a couple of times just to accommodate him.
And the same Catholic church outside of Bryan, what is it, St. Joseph?
St. Joseph.
They were the only Catholic church I can remember.
Well, normally the cadets kept to themselves about their religion.
Now, the fact that you were of Greek ancestry, did that ever, did anybody ever tease you about that?
No, sir.
Never did.
And describe the variety of acquaintances you had here as to where they came from and what their family did.
Well, one of my
Battery Mates was Cantu, Peter Cantu.
He was from San Antonio and his family had a grocery store if I'm not mistaken.
Normally, generally, Cadet Corps was a great mixture of different religion, different nationality, and no one ever questioned.
No one.
Like, did you know some Jewish boys?
Oh, yeah.
Bob Epstein, and I knew some Italian boys named Cantina from Galveston, Novelli, and some Jewish.
But we were all friends.
No one ever questioned.
Were any of those Japanese American boys from Orange County here when you were here?
Oh, Kishi.
No, they were before my time.
They were rice farmers down in Viter, Texas, Orange County.
That's correct.
Got a good memory, Dr. Monroe.
Let's see.
When the war started, did everything become more serious on campus?
I can't say that it was a change of pace or anything like that because to me A&M was always a serious situation you know.
There wasn't no hell raising much and silver taps just sobered you up so quickly and made you realize that life is so precious you know.
Yeah, the activity has begun to pick up in the military and fellows, classmates were leaving before they finished the semester.
Did all of y'all take Silver Tap seriously?
Yes, sir.
That was the most serious thing that was on this campus.
Today, I can tell you
